as a grade school kid many years ago i 'd come home at lunchtime to a bowl of chicken noodle soup and a package of ritz crackers . i love to put them in my soup , since they would cool it off a bit and i could eat it more quickly . when i grew up i started eating ritz crackers with some peanut butter spread on them and topped with a dab of honey . what i like best about these crackers is that they have n't changed over the years . it 's been well over half a century since i 'd eat them at lunch with my chicken noodle soup . but they still have the same rich taste today . and they 're pretty low in sodium and fat , which today is an important consideration .

having lived in italy for some qqq plus years -- i find barilla pasta to be quite good pasta !

" barilla makes good pasta . " this is a quote from my ex 's mother that lives in italy . i do n't argue with her - ever . as for the name ... "chitarra " , literally translated , means " guitar " , which perfectly describes the shape of this pasta once you know how it is made . this is a " cut " pasta ( like fettucine ) as opposed to an " extruded " pasta that is pressed through holes ( e.g. ; spaghetti ) . it is thin like spaghetti , but it a square cut . this is because the pasta is traditionally made by hand by rolling into sheets and then placed on the " chitarra " device ( looks a bit like a loom ) . using a rolling pin , the pasta is pushed through the strings which cuts it and gives it a " square " shape . the pasta is traditionally served with a meat ragu , but you can use it pretty much anywhere you would use spaghetti to give your dish a fun twist . i used to bring this pasta back from my trips to italy , but this product does the job and is readily available in the states .

i got qqq different types of these - a tube of gel ( swagger ) , a jar of pomade , and a jar of putty . i tried them all on both myself and my husband . he has darker brown hair , long ( mid - back ) , and very thick . i have very light hair , shoulder length , and very fine . of the three , we both like the gel best . i 'm not sure i even see a difference between the pomade and putty , they both even smelled quite similar ( no special fragrance was listed ) . the gel goes on lighter , to me , and has a much lighter feel to it . if you 're trying to make spikes , then maybe the putty or pomade would be better , the gel would n't have held hair up like that , but the other two would have . for myself , though , i just wanted some lift . fine hair can be pretty flat . the gel gives me that without feeling weighed down or noticeable . both the pomade and the putty left a noticeable residue . it was more visible on my lighter hair than his darker , but you could still tell . both of them are also very unpleasant to touch . kind of grit - like and sticky . i love playing with his hair , so that just would n't do . the swagger scent is also quite pleasant . it reminds me of an older men 's cologne i ca n't think of the name of . maybe a light version of polo or the original hugo boss , but not sure . i 'm very picky about scents , though , and this one worked for me . both jars had similar scents - nothing specific just light and fresh - ish , not bad at all .

when i first saw this product years ago , i thought , " why would someone need to , or want to , spray their shower , every day ? " well , friends , because if you do n't you * will * have mold and mildew growing on your tiles . ever since i tried this those many years ago i have never looked back . this tilex fresh shower refill is constantly stocked in my household for whenever my sprayer runs low . it is a good value , and less wasteful than buying a new spray bottle every time you run out . to use , you * must * first do a deep scrubbing of your shower / bath . if you do not , it will only take longer for this to work ; it 's better to start off with a clean slate in this instance . once your shower / bath is clean , all you have left is daily maintenance . you do that by spraying right after every shower , while everything is still wet , on wet surfaces . that 's it . repeat after every shower ( i usually do n't spray more than twice a day ) . i spray my tiles , my non - slip mat ( especially this ) , and my shower - head . do n't spray on dry surfaces , it wo n't be as effective . one original spray bottle lasts about a month if you use it every day . this refill bottle will fill up two more times after that . if you are more forgetful , or just do n't want to physically spray every day , i recommend the <a data - hook="product - link - linked " class="a - link - normal " href="/scrubbing - bubbles - automatic - shower - cleaner / dp / qqq / ref = cm_cr_arp_d_rvw_txt?ie = qqq bubbles automatic shower cleaner</a > . you press a button and it does it automatically for you , but it does n't cover as much surface area compared to you doing it manually , and it 's more expensive ( the cost of being lazy you know ) . for me , i would rather spray every day and maintain a clean shower than having to go in and scrub every so often . recommended .

i 've had very good luck with the k - cup version of this tea , moreso than the bags . the tea itself is good , quite good , and soothing after a long day . the k - cup formulation , at a smaller cup setting , gives a very good serving of this tea . it 's not overly strong , yet not so weak that it might as well be regular water . indeed , i caution against the medium or large cup sizes . the small is all you need . i 've also tried this in regular keurig machines as well as a hamilton beach flexbrew system . the difference here is that the keurig uses pressurized water whereas the flexbrew uses a drip system . frankly , i think this tea benefits more from the drip system as it is n't as harsh with the tea leaves . it may be my imagination , but i like the tea more out of the flexbrew . either way , this is a good tea , one of the standards of the celestial seasonings line ... and for good reason . it has good flavor notes and aromas that relax and help you unwind . the k - cup format enhances those qualities i think , and allow for a more consistent tea . a good product !

the product is n't bad . it seems to leave a little bit of film at first , but over time , i think it worked fairly well . i am very disappointed in the fragrance though . it says " we think clean smells like fresh mint leaves " and the scent is eucalyptus mint . if they say so . i purchased this for the mint scent , but it does n't smell at all like mint . it smells like faux pine or balsam scent , and i find it gaggy . also every time i use the product , i have to cover my face so i do n't breath any of it since it makes me cough . i thought this was a natural product , but some , not all , of the ingredients and somewhat questionable . for instance hexyl cinnamalhyde , a derivative of chamomile , which is used for scent . the scent , by the way , is a jasmine substitute in fragrances . people w / sensitive skin should be especially careful using products w / this ingredient because it causes dermatitis in some . then there 's benzisothiazolinone , it is used on an industrial level as a biocide on buildings ( to kill fungus on roofs and buildings ) as well as a preservative in paints and cleaning products . has been found that when used in air freshener products , benzisothiazolinone is cytotoxic to lung cells , creating free radical damage to these cells . exposure can lead to allergic contact dermatitis and skin sensitization . the scientific committee on consumer safety ( eu ) has advised that it not be used in personal care items due to lack of data as well as its potential for skin sensitization . animal studies have observed reproductive effects when administered orally at high doses . ( concentrations in household / personal care products are thought not to be high enough to have an effect on human reproduction , however . ) this product concerns me because you 're using a spray and are bound to have some mist airborne . sure you want a well ventilated room and all that , but a shower is often a confined space . perhaps that 's why i , personally , have issues breathing when using this product . and there are people out there who knowingly or unknowingly are allergic to a couple of the ingredients in this product . so , if you like the product and none of these issues are relevant to you , great , but if you have n't tried the product , keep these in mind when you make your decision .

i 'm not writing this review based on the taste of the salsa . at this point , we should all know what pace tastes like . no , it is n't as good as the salsa i make fresh from garden tomatoes , jalapeos and onions or the salsa you get at authentic mexican restaurants . that said , my kids will still eat this like crazy . paired with pretzels , it 's a decent after school snack . paired with the $ qqq stuff and stand taco shells i found in amazon pantry , it makes for a cheap dinner and very kid friendly . the five star review comes from the price . we go through a lot of salsa . i live in a very rural oklahoma community and we have a local grocery store chain that specializes in small towns without chain stores . while i 'm so grateful that store is there , it also comes with pretty big mark ups . i called today for an exact post tax price for their qqq ounce bottle and it was $ qqq . so it is basically three times higher and they do n't ship it to my front door . all and all , it 's still a pretty good salsa and i like the chunky better than the regular . i know from other pace products it will preserve well . the nice part is this size means we wo n't run out quickly . also , the larger plastic bottle with the handle will serve nicely for a dog food scoop or to hold homemade dressing when i make it . overall , pretty killer savings for a rural person taking advtange of the prime program . included a photo to show the quantity difference for essentially the same price .

volume , my a$$. this mascara barely gives you any volume . however , what it does is give you a surprising amount of length . for reference , i have very sparse , straight upper lashes , and almost none at all on the bottom . my natural length is okay --- my problem is just that i do n't have enough hairs , and the ones that i have are very fine . i love getting actual eyelash extensions done for special occasions , but they only last about qqq weeks before they start falling out , and i 'm not skillful enough to master false eyelashes on a daily basis , so my only other option is a good mascara . in the photos below you can see how this mascara did on my wimpy lashes . the first photo is my clean lashes , no eye makeup . the second is with one coat of clump crusher extensions . the third photo is with two coats . one coat looks pretty natural , and adds some color and length , but no real volume . two coats is where the trouble starts . the lashes start looking like twigs , with small unnatural clumping at the tips , instead the normal hair shape , which is fuller at the base and tapered at the tip . that 's different than adding smooth volume to each hair shaft . on the bright side , the black color is very black . the brush is one of those small spiky brushes , and the curve sets it apart from the regular clump crusher brush . compared to the regular clump crusher , the clump crusher extensions adds more length , but is more or less the same . neither one is life changing , so i 'll keep looking for my holy grail mascara .

i tried two of the kind fruit and nut bars side by side the almond & coconut and then the almond & apricot and they 're both very tasty . the top three ingredients for both bars are almonds , coconut , and honey but the coconut flavor only comes through in the almond & coconut the apricot dominates the other bar . i think both are good , but i d probably choose the almond & coconut if i was to buy a large quantity some people may get sick of the apricot . in terms of nutrition , each qqq gram bar contains a combined qqq grams of carbs and fat , qqq grams fiber and qqq grams protein . just under one third is sugar ( qqq or qqq grams ) , and the carbs protein ratio is higher than ideal . that would nt put me off eating another one ( as long as they were n't a daily thing ) but i m more turned off by the company itself for reasons ill go into below . based on their marketing , you would think that kind is the top choice from an ethical perspective . they donate $ qqq per month to various causes . but to put that into perspective , kinds sales were close to $ qqq million in qqq and $ qqq million in qqq . they donate $ qqq per month , so that s $ qqq k per year , or qqq % of their sales revenue for qqq ( probably less than qqq % of qqq revenue ) . this is a very small fraction of the amount donated by companies that have joined the qqq % for the planet program . clif have their own foundation and donate qqq % of revenue ( for clif and luna bars ) to various social and environmental causes . do nt get me wrong , i think that they are making an effort to do good things , but its good to put things into perspective . how about the social and environmental impact of the company itself ? i could find nothing on the companys use of energy and materials , sourcing of ingredients , etc . these issues come first corporate donations to charity ( at a miniscule fraction of sales revenue in this case ) should be an add - on after every effort is made in the material sourcing and manufacturing process to reduce social and environmental impact . compare this to clif , who have a lot to say about their use of green energy , sourcing of sustainable and organic ingredients , reduction of packaging waste , etc . kinds lack of transparency is concerning and i feel that the goodwill they have built is entirely based on their relatively very small charitable donations a great pr exercise but i feel that that s qqq % of what it is . kind makes no statements about the ethics of their palm oil and cacao sources - does this mean that the kind company is responsible for deforestation and child slavery ? i would really like to see some information on the company and ingredients all they have to say is that they use non - gmo ingredients . compare to clif , which uses qqq % organic ingredients and has certified their cacao and palm oil . so , in the end kind bars tasted better than i expected but their social and environmental impact did not meet my expectations . hopefully they will release more data on their impact as a company but until then i d rather just eat some nuts or trail mix than buy a kind bar . i think the kind fruit and nuts bars deserve qqq gold stars for quality and taste , but only qqq green stars for social and environmental impact .

whoever invented parchment paper for baking deserves a nobel prize . it 's a no - brainer for keeping pans clean , and for turning out perfect cookies . i used to buy the rolls , but struggling with cutting the right size to fit my baking sheets was not a good time ( i 'd used up several rolls before i realized you use the paper sideways ) . anyway , reynolds has developed a product that will save time and tempers with these individual parchment paper baking sheets . they 're already sized for standard cookie sheets so you can devote your time and energy to the actual cookies , or whatever you 're making . i actually bake meatloaf on parchment paper ; it allows the top and sides to develop a delicious crust instead of just the top . the reynolds parchment paper is good quality . it 's actually reusable one time ; though it gets brown and gnarly looking , the taste of the cookies are fine . i would n't recommend using it more than once if you 're baking anything with meat in it , or if your pastry is really buttery . yes , they 're a bit pricey for a product that 's a convenience , but rolls of parchment paper are n't that cheap either . i do n't bake very often , and i 'm thrilled to have a box of these on hand for when i do . anything that makes life a little easier is a winner in my book .

these come folded into qqq , so when you open them up , there 's a crease in the form of a cross . i 've had other boxes where the papers were folded in half , but those boxes are a lot harder to store , and constantly were falling off the shelf . this is a much more convenient , easier to store box size . they are a bit more expensive than rolls , but it is nice not having to fight with curled edges . i unfold the sheets , and put that center point upside down , so that the center point is up , forming a bit of a tent . then i put my cookies or bread on top of it , and they hold it down . i find that cookies and breads absolutely do not stick , and they brown much more evenly than if you just put the cookies directly on the pan . i do think that silicone baking mats make the browning a bit more even , but the advantage of these is that when done , they can simply be thrown away , and they are easy to store and do n't take up a lot of space . also , these can be cut to fit different size pans , if needed . i find that i can use the same paper over and over again for most cookies . after that first batch , the paper lays flat and the crease is gone . for instance , i just baked some tollhouse chocolate chip cookies , and the recipe calls for the oven on qqq . i was able to use the same sheet for qqq batches and it performed as well on the first as the last . when i was done , i threw the paper away , and the pan was still clean . if you have ever known the horror of trying to wash a pan that had really stuck cookies , like i have , you will appreciate having the sheets around even more . i also use these for making stromboli and cheddar jalapeno bread , which i make in a simple boule . they work as well for breads as they do cookies , and these are also , in my opinion , a must use if you are making jellyrolls . nothing i 've ever cooked has stuck to parchment paper .

this product was on sale with prime pantry so i thought i 'd try it . i should state that i normally use seventh generation toilet bowl cleaner ( and a regular brush ) , so this product was quite a departure from what i 'm used to , but i figured i would give it a try and maybe use it for quick cleaning when i was in a hurry . in short , i am not impressed with this product , and here are my reasons why . first , the disposable " sponge " you attach to the handle is very small . this is adequate for cleaning the bowl where there is no water ( and i think it works decently under the rim , unlike some other reviewers , though a brush can do more ) and should work well for most of the bowl if you manage to mostly drain it first , though you need some water to " activate " the cleaning product on the sponge . however , seems too small and perhaps not abrasive enough to adequately clean near the " drain " area at the bottom of the bowl , which is where i find hard water deposits . second , the cleaning product is apparently dyed blue , which darkens the water to such an extent that it 's hard to actually see what you 're doing and whether your efforts to clean are actually making a difference . third , the cleaning product is very bubbly , which also makes it hard to see what you 're doing ( i know , i know , people think that bubbles mean that it 's working , but other products i use bubble less and still clean effectively ) . finally , i do n't think germaphobes will appreciate this product as much as they think they will : because the sponge is so small , some of the handle will have to get dipped in the water in order for you to clean , especially at the bottom of the bowl -- although i guess the handle is easier to clean than a brush . ( just make sure it 's dry before you put it back in the holder or it will drop onto your floor . personally , i spray the handle with a disinfecting cleaner and let it dry before putting it back . ) in the future , i will stick with my other cleaning products . the " natural " cleaners i 've used clean just as well , if not better , and i find a traditional brush more effective at cleaning and easier to use .

i use this in a bread maker ( up to the dough cycle , then shape and bake it in the oven ) as the base for a variety of breads . for some i add garlic and/or herbs , such as oregano , basil , thyme . i also made an " apple bread " to celebrate apple season this fall . i just use the directions on the box and do not change anything when i add the other ingredients except for adding about an additional half teaspoon of yeast . i find that shaping it as shown on the box is not as satisfactory as baking it in a bread pan , but the best result is with a " bread cloche " ( i use an old ceramic coated cast iron little dutch oven instead of an expensive cloche . ) my way of getting a browned chewy crust with a soft inside is on the final egg wash -- i add about a half teaspoon of tapioca starch ( any other starch would probably work ) to the beaten egg yolk , spread it on the loaf for the last five minutes of baking , and it always comes out with a wonderful dark chewy crust ( not just for this particular bread mix , but for any other i have tried . ) these bread mixes may add up to a more expensive loaf than starting from scratch , and a mix and bread maker may not satisfy those whose ego want to say they made it from scratch , but the convenience is certainly worth the little difference in price , i get my ego trips elsewhere , and whenever i see the label " krusteaz " on a box i feel i can trust the product .
